3. lymphata, ‘ frenzied,' with the Bacchic enthusiasm. The origin of this curious word is obscure. Probably Nympha and lympha were connected or confused in popular etymology, so that the Greek νυμφόληπτος- Nymph possessed, benymphed—came to be rendered in Latin by lymphatus. For the belief that the Nymphs possessed the power of inspiring madness and delirium, see Heroides, iv. 49-50, where Phaedra likens herself in her fits of frenzy to
